{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7de49e56-b8c4-44e3-aa21-b376ac5dc2dc","content":"With Microsoft.Testing.Platform, VSTest adapter flags move to platform-native switches passed after `--`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  -- \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nYou'll also need these NuGet packages in your test project:\n\n| Old mechanism | New package |\n|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\n**Key differences:**\n- `--filter` stays before `--` (it's understood by `dotnet test` itself).\n- Everything after `--` is forwarded directly to the test platform.\n- Cobertura format is now a separate flag (`--coverage-output-format`) rather than a semicolon parameter.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a83e6d00-8b0b-49c5-92f8-47f592c7042e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling, not a codebase task. Let me provide the answer directly.\n\nKey changes when moving to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n1. `dotnet test` still works but the arguments change\n2. `--filter` becomes `--filter` (same) or `--treenode-filter` for the new filter syntax\n3. `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx`\n4. `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` - Microsoft.Testing.Platform has its own code coverage integration, typically `--collect \"Microsoft Code Coverage\"` or you use `--coverage` with Microsoft.CodeCoverage\n\n\n5. Blame-related options like `--blame-crash`, `--blame-hang`, and `--blame-hang-timeout` map to `--crashdump`, `--hangdump`, and `--hangdump-timeout` respectively. When running the test app directly rather than through `dotnet test`, the filter syntax changes to `--treenode-filter`, and you'll need the Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport package for TRX report generation.\n\nI'm realizing there's a distinction between how `dotnet test` wraps the test platform versus running the test app directly, and I need to clarify which approach applies in different scenarios. I need to pull in the required NuGet packages to enable those platform-specific features—the trx reporting, code coverage, crash dump, and hang dump extensions all come from separate Microsoft.Testing packages.","outputTokens":1143,"requestId":"340A:6A01C:76F6F12:833F99A:69F3FAFF"},"id":"b0e7409f-0040-49e1-a26d-ec40f95bf533","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:00:03.374Z","parentId":"713f3d34-a2b8-4920-afb5-97de7ed57c3c"}
